{{italic title}} {{Zen Buddhism}} '''''Book of Equanimity''''' or '''''Book of Serenity''''' or '''''Book of Composure''''' (Chinese: 從容錄, Cóngróng lù; Japanese: 従容錄, ''Shōyōroku'') is the title of a book compiled by [[Wansong Xingxiu]] (1166–1246), and first published in 1224. The book comprises a collection of 100 [[koan]]s written by the [[Chan Buddhism|Chan Buddhist]] master [[Hongzhi Zhengjue]] (1091–1157), together with commentaries by Wansong. Wansong's compilation is the only surviving source for Hongzhi's koans.<ref>{{Cite book | last1=Buswell Jr. | first1=Robert E. | last2=Lopez Jr. | first2=Donald S. | title=The Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism | publisher=Princeton University Press | year=2013 | isbn=9781400848058 | page=197 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=O'Brien|first=Barbara|title=Introduction to Koans|url=http://buddhism.about.com/od/chanandzenbuddhism/a/Introduction-To-Koans.htm|publisher=[[About.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wick| first=Gerry Shishin |authorlink=Gerry Shishin Wick |title=The Book Of Equanimity: Illuminating Classic Zen Koans |page=2 |publisher=Wisdom Publications |isbn=9780861713875 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite book |last=Leighton| first=Taigen Dan |authorlink=Taigen Dan Leighton |title=Cultivating the Empty Field: The Silent Illumination of Zen Master Hongzhi |page=5 |publisher=Tuttle Publishing |isbn=9780804832403 }}</ref>
Along with ''[[The Gateless Barrier]]'', the ''Book of Equanimity'' is considered one of the two primary compilations of [[Zen]] dialogue.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reviews: Book of Serenity / The Gateless Barrier|last=Hamill |first=Sam|url=http://www.tricycle.com/reviews/book-serenity-gateless-barrier| publisher=[[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review]]}}</ref> [[Shohaku Okumura]] has called the collection "a classic text that is still studied by Zen students today."<ref>{{cite book |last=Okumura| first=Shohaku |authorlink=Shohaku Okumura |title=Realizing Genjokoan |page=158 |publisher=Wisdom Publications |isbn=9780861716012 }}</ref> [[Reb Anderson]] has called it "an auspicious peak in the mountain range of Zen literature, a subtle flowing stream in the deep valleys of our teaching, a treasure house of inspiration and guidance in studying the ocean of Buddhist teachings."<ref>{{cite web|title=Book of Serenity: One Hundred Zen Dialogues|url=http://www.shambhala.com/book-of-serenity.html|publisher=[[Shambhala Publications]]|access-date=2013-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305023959/http://www.shambhala.com/book-of-serenity.html#|archive-date=2013-03-05|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> [[Gerry Shishin Wick]], who published a translation of ''Book of Equanimity'' in 2005, says "although it was collected by a master in the Soto lineage, The Book of Equanimity, they are treated as Koans in the Rinzai, some Rinzai schools, and the Soto school studied them, but more as liturgy, rather than as Koans."<ref>{{cite web|title=BG 109: Koan Training and the Different Styles of Zen|url=http://www.buddhistgeeks.com/2009/02/bg-109-koan-training-and-the-different-styles-of-zen/|publisher=[[Buddhist Geeks]]|access-date=2013-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130415145409/http://www.buddhistgeeks.com/2009/02/bg-109-koan-training-and-the-different-styles-of-zen/#|archive-date=2013-04-15|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
